{"key":"processedPost-8909307","value":{"id":8909307,"first":8908247,"last":8913278,"when":1221102734,"utime":"09/11/08 06:12 AM","cleanedPost":"Actually, if a straw log is pinning, you can dump a thick layer of salt on the trich to hold it in check long enough to get your flush.&nbsp; That is ONLY if it's a tiny spot of green.&nbsp; Apply salt to at least 1\" past the edges of the trich.&nbsp; The salt will kill the mushroom mycelium <i>and</i> the mold mycelium in that spot.&nbsp; The green will appear in other places within a week, but hopefully, your first flush will be done by then.&nbsp; At that time, salt all the green spots and haul the log to the trash or an outdoor area where it can probably fruit again.<br />I actually have a video filmed of me saving a straw log from trich this way.&nbsp; I seriously need to get finished editing and get it up on my site, since I filmed it over a year ago.&nbsp; In the video, I mixed a shotglass of salt with a few drops of water to make a paste and applied it.<br />The slimy area was probably just on the bottom where water pooled up and didn't drain properly.&nbsp; I always punch a row of holes after I get the log in position, so they're on the very bottom to drain water that flows from gravity to the bottom.&nbsp; It needs a path to escape. A bit of bacteria isn't a problem with bulk substrates.&nbsp; If you can get it dried out a little, the mycelium will eat it for lunch.<br />RR"}}